==English==

===Alternative forms===
* [[abecedary]]

===Etymology===
* From {{etyl|LL.}} {{term|abecedarius}} (from the first four letters of the Latin alphabet + {{term|-arius|lang=la}})
* {{suffix|abecedary|an}}. 
* Compare {{term|abecedary}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/eɪ.biː.siːˈdɛː.ɹɪ.ən/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˌeɪ.biˌsiˈdɛ.ɹi.ən/|/ˌeɪ.biˌsiˈdæɹ.i.ən/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}
{{examples-right|sense=rhetoric|examples=He knew the rhetorical devices, from abecedarian, battologia, and contentio, all the way to zeugma}}
# Someone who is learning the alphabet.
# An [[elementary]] student, a [[novice]]; one in the early steps of learning. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
#*'''1603''', {{w|John Florio}}, translating Michel de Montaigne, ''Essays'', II.28:
#*:A man may alwaies continue his studie, but not schooling. O fond-foolish for an old man to be ever an '''''Abcedarian''''' {{transterm|abecedaire}}.
